{
  "ir_hash": "sha256:63e6aabb1fc8d0ed303f7cc9bbdc82a7ad8419c3a48d782cbd341c24906e27b4",
  "knowledges": [
    {
      "content": "An *RL-fine-tuned LLM* is a language model whose post-training step updates its policy via reinforcement learning against a task-level reward (verifier-checked answer correctness, format compliance, tool success, ...). The dominant family of algorithms in this regime is **GRPO** (Group Relative Policy Optimization) and its descendants, which estimate per-token advantages by comparing a sampled group of rollouts against the group mean rather than against a learned value baseline. The policy and the optimiser update share a single parameter set, so all per-sample token-level gradients are summed into one step.",
      "content_hash": "2afbcf36dfbed227b2115137d912e90f4c8c4f04bb1b5800354412705e6c4866",
      "declaration_index": 0,
      "exported": false,
      "id": "github:2604_06159_tpo_target_policy_optimization::llm_rl_setting",
      "label": "llm_rl_setting",
      "module": "motivation",
      "parameters": [],
      "title": "LLM policy-gradient RL fine-tuning (formal setting)",
      "type": "setting"
    },
    {
      "content": "The study scope of TPO is the *training rule* used during this RL fine-tuning step -- how the per-token learning signal is constructed from a batch of rollouts. A *target policy* is a reference token distribution (e.g. derived from the best-of-group rollout, an expert demonstration, or a frozen reference model) that the trainee policy is asked to match on the supervised positions, supplying a dense token-level signal that the sparse group-relative advantage alone does not. TPO replaces (or augments) the GRPO group-relative policy-gradient term with a cross-entropy term against this target policy.",
      "content_hash": "bb9c4cfa8b8368b733e2fefe2c347fffc120326e21037e0abf2418f1f8bb7310",
      "declaration_index": 1,
      "exported": false,
      "id": "github:2604_06159_tpo_target_policy_optimization::target_policy_scope",
      "label": "target_policy_scope",
      "module": "motivation",
      "parameters": [],
      "title": "Target-policy training rule (study scope)",
      "type": "setting"
    },
    {
      "content": "Policy-gradient RL fine-tuning of LLMs benefits from optimising the trainee policy against an explicit **target policy** -- a reference token distribution constructed from the rollouts -- rather than relying solely on the group-relative return signal used by GRPO and its descendants. The target policy supplies a dense, token-level supervisory signal that is well-defined per token (via cross-entropy) and that does not exhibit the destructive per-sample gradient competition that arises when a sparse group-relative advantage is back-propagated through every token of every rollout in a group.",
      "content_hash": "94bca46d8ea28085568ef72bba8ba9a9aafd919d6546a958fb7db6631b028b69",
      "declaration_index": 2,
      "exported": true,
      "id": "github:2604_06159_tpo_target_policy_optimization::target_policy_is_the_optimisation_object",
      "label": "target_policy_is_the_optimisation_object",
      "metadata": {
        "prior": 0.9,
        "prior_justification": "The central thesis is encoded directly in the paper's title ('Target Policy Optimization'). The framing -- that an explicit target policy should be the optimisation object during LLM RL fine-tuning -- is the authors' headline contribution, so the claim is well-evidenced *as the paper's stated position*. Held below 0.95 because, having only the title, we cannot inspect how strongly the body argues for target-policy primacy versus the softer 'target policy alongside GRPO advantage' position, nor can we verify the exact construction of the target.",
        "source": "artifacts/2604.06159-tpo-target-policy-optimization.md (H1 / title)"
      },
      "module": "motivation",
      "parameters": [],
      "title": "Central thesis: target-policy optimisation as the right RL training rule",
      "type": "claim"
    },
    {
      "content": "**TPO** -- the method named in the title -- is proposed as the concrete realisation of that training rule: it specifies how the target policy is constructed from a batch of rollouts and how the trainee policy is updated against it (a cross-entropy objective on the supervised positions), positioning itself as a drop-in alternative to GRPO-family algorithms for RL-fine-tuning reasoning LLMs.",
      "content_hash": "ad6d5233aad49f9f0ec1def03fe3de924c5c3026c6c8a610a3efb3d4c2087fb3",
      "declaration_index": 3,
      "exported": true,
      "id": "github:2604_06159_tpo_target_policy_optimization::tpo_realises_target_policy_optimization",
      "label": "tpo_realises_target_policy_optimization",
      "metadata": {
        "prior": 0.88,
        "prior_justification": "Implied directly by the leading 'TPO:' in the title -- the naming convention 'METHOD: thesis' is the standard way authors signal that METHOD is their proposed realisation of the thesis. Held slightly lower than the thesis itself because 'realises a training rule' is a strong claim and title-only evidence cannot distinguish a complete algorithm specification from an early framework sketch, nor pin down the precise update form (pure cross-entropy vs. cross-entropy + auxiliary GRPO term, on-policy vs. off-policy target construction, etc.).",
        "source": "artifacts/2604.06159-tpo-target-policy-optimization.md (title: 'TPO:')"
      },
      "module": "motivation",
      "parameters": [],
      "title": "TPO realises target policy optimization",
      "type": "claim"
    },
    {
      "content": "The work is situated within **RL training** of LLMs -- TPO is a training-time algorithm applied during the reinforcement-learning fine-tuning step (where the policy is updated against task-level verifier rewards), not a decoding-time strategy or a supervised fine-tuning recipe.",
      "content_hash": "73be73afcf1805e50eeb71eb60e689cf63121eb0506a48616e423daae0e8d64a",
      "declaration_index": 4,
      "exported": true,
      "id": "github:2604_06159_tpo_target_policy_optimization::keyword_rl_training",
      "label": "keyword_rl_training",
      "metadata": {
        "gaia": {
          "provenance": {
            "referenced_claims": [
              "llm_rl_setting",
              "target_policy_is_the_optimisation_object",
              "target_policy_scope",
              "tpo_realises_target_policy_optimization"
            ]
          }
        },
        "keyword_index": 1,
        "source": "artifacts/2604.06159-tpo-target-policy-optimization.md (keywords)"
      },
      "module": "motivation",
      "parameters": [],
      "title": "Keyword: rl-training",
      "type": "claim"
    },
    {
      "content": "TPO positions itself as a **GRPO alternative** -- a drop-in replacement for Group Relative Policy Optimization and its descendants in the standard reasoning-LLM RL-fine-tuning pipeline. It targets the same task family (verifier-rewarded reasoning), the same data interface (groups of sampled rollouts per prompt), and the same place in the training stack, but substitutes a different per-token learning signal.",
      "content_hash": "883d2e74b91676eed4bdec788cbe59e4f4fc47d87493eddca1d898d00c687f59",
      "declaration_index": 5,
      "exported": true,
      "id": "github:2604_06159_tpo_target_policy_optimization::keyword_grpo_alternative",
      "label": "keyword_grpo_alternative",
      "metadata": {
        "gaia": {
          "provenance": {
            "referenced_claims": [
              "llm_rl_setting",
              "target_policy_is_the_optimisation_object",
              "target_policy_scope",
              "tpo_realises_target_policy_optimization"
            ]
          }
        },
        "keyword_index": 2,
        "source": "artifacts/2604.06159-tpo-target-policy-optimization.md (keywords)"
      },
      "module": "motivation",
      "parameters": [],
      "title": "Keyword: grpo-alternative",
      "type": "claim"
    },
    {
      "content": "The supervisory signal in TPO has the form of a **cross-entropy** term against the constructed target policy: on the supervised token positions the trainee policy is asked to match the target distribution under cross-entropy, rather than to follow a sparse group-relative policy-gradient. Cross-entropy is the natural form for a target-policy training rule because it is dense per token and does not require an advantage estimate.",
      "content_hash": "0be53837de63943ea7e60512e2b08e31966c34d754173006c49e2bd0d4426155",
      "declaration_index": 6,
      "exported": true,
      "id": "github:2604_06159_tpo_target_policy_optimization::keyword_cross_entropy",
      "label": "keyword_cross_entropy",
      "metadata": {
        "gaia": {
          "provenance": {
            "referenced_claims": [
              "target_policy_is_the_optimisation_object",
              "target_policy_scope",
              "tpo_realises_target_policy_optimization"
            ]
          }
        },
        "keyword_index": 3,
        "source": "artifacts/2604.06159-tpo-target-policy-optimization.md (keywords)"
      },
      "module": "motivation",
      "parameters": [],
      "title": "Keyword: cross-entropy",
      "type": "claim"
    },
    {
      "content": "The failure mode of the GRPO baseline that TPO is designed to avoid is **gradient conflict** -- the per-sample token-level gradients within a single GRPO group point in opposing directions in shared parameter subspaces (e.g. a high-advantage rollout pushes a token up while a low-advantage rollout in the same group pushes the same token down), so that the summed update degrades the underlying reasoning behaviour. A target-policy cross-entropy objective sidesteps this conflict because all supervised tokens share a single coherent target.",
      "content_hash": "400543d964a96c7aacbb842163e3e4c3c8257e20978c10a3b98f17382af352f0",
      "declaration_index": 7,
      "exported": true,
      "id": "github:2604_06159_tpo_target_policy_optimization::keyword_gradient_conflict",
      "label": "keyword_gradient_conflict",
      "metadata": {
        "gaia": {
